The data used here concern a questionnaire on hobbies. 8403 individuals were asked to answer questions about their hobbies (18 questions). The following four variables were used to describe the individuals: sex (male, female), age (15-25, 26-35, 36-45, 46-55, 56-65, 66-75, 76-85, 86-100), marital status (single, married, widowed,divorced, remarried), profession (manual laborer, unskilled worker, technician, foreman, senior management, employee, other). And finally, a quantitative variable indicates the number of hobbies practiced out of the 18 possible choices.

#By looking at the summary of both distributions we are able to observe what are the x-squared values of each Chi-squared distribution. This distribution measures the significance level between two variables, and with a p-value equal to 1 there is a 100% risk of concluding an association between the variables when there is no actual association. 
#Then, since the x-squared value of 'Pro_Read' is higher than  the one of 'Pro_Cine', 0.076>0.058, respectively, we can conclude that there is a stronger association between Reading and Profession rather than Cinema and Profession. 
#To check the veracity of these statements, the Cramer's V for each distribution will be calculated

results <- chisq.test(Pro_Cine)
## Warning in chisq.test(Pro_Cine): Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect
results
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  Pro_Cine
## X-squared = 0.058829, df = 6, p-value = 1
#get the observed counts
results$observed

##   Other            -0.011911492  0.011911492
Phi2_Cine <- results$statistic/sum(Pro_Cine)
#Number of Categories for variable Y
J_Cine <- ncol(Pro_Cine) 
#Number of Categories for variable X
I_Cine <- nrow(Pro_Cine)
#Degree of Freedom
(I_Cine-1)*(J_Cine-1) 
## [1] 6
max_Phi_Cine <- (min(I_Cine,J_Cine)-1)
#Calculate the X-squared
Phi2_Cine/max_Phi_Cine
##  X-squared 
## 0.05882894
#Calculate the Cramers V, which gives us the measure of association between two variables. It is a number between 0 and 1
V_Cine <- sqrt(results$statistic/(sum(Pro_Cine)*(min(I_Cine,J_Cine)-1)))

Multiple Correspondence Analysis

  1. Use again the data set hobbies. Perform an MCA using the function MCA to investigate if an association exists among the different activities (hint use the first 18 variables as active variables and the last 5 variables as supplementary qualitative and/or quantitative variables.
MCA_hobbies <- MCA(hobbies,ncp = 5,quanti.sup=23,quali.sup=19:22,graph=T,method="Burt")

How you will interpret the first dimension?

#First of all, we need to mention the difference between the contribution of a variable to a dimension and the correlation of this same variable with the dimension. The contribution gives us how much a dimension explains a variable, whereas the correlation explains how much the variables are affected by the dimension.
#By looking at the previously plotted graph we can observe that, in the first dimension, there are different groups of categories that in between them share similar levels of correlation and contribution to the dimension. The first one is composed by the variables Exhibition, Show and Cinema. This group has a high contribution and a high correlation, which means that these variables are little explained by other dimensions, and that are strongly affected by dimension 1. The second group of variables is composed by Traveling, Sport and Computer. This group has a medium/low contribution and a high correlation. This means that these variables, even if strongly affected by the first dimension, can be greatly explained by other dimensions. The last group consists of variables with low contribution and correlation, such as Gardening, Mechanic and Cooking. These categories are not explained by the first dimension and not affected by it.
#Given all this information, we can state with a substantial degree of confidence that the first dimension represents the Leisure hobbies, with an inclination towards arts. This goes in accordance with the variables that have a high correlation and contribution. On the other hand, the variables of the group with high correlation and low/medium contribution also support this statement, given that Traveling, Sport and Computer can be clearly Leisure activities, which means that are affected by a dimension like the one we described, but  at the same time can be describe by other dimension. A clear example is that we can play sports competitively and not as a Leisure and free time activity. Lastly, the third dimension we described, also supports the previous characterization given that any of the activities in this group cannot be clearly seen as a Leisure activity, and none of them are related to arts, which means that will never be affected or described by a dimension like this.
